<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">I often have to go work in Algeria for short trips and I find trying to type using a french keyboard layout a major issue. The original qwerty typewriters were designed to put the most common english letters as far apart as possible. The french did the same but using a different language they had a different frequency distribution of letters and so required a different layout. Result? The azerty keyboard instead of qwerty.
<br />

<br />
See this webapge for what I mean:
<br />
<a href="http://www.terena.nl/library/multiling/ml-mua/test/kbd-all.html#French" target="_blank">http://www.terena.nl/library/multiling/ml-mua/test/kbd-all.htmlNum.French</a>
<br />

<br />
What makes this issue even worse is that some of the PC's I have to work with in Algeria are poorly configured and misrecongnise the french azerty keyboards as 101 key us qwerty keyboards making typing anything longer than a few words an horendoues exercise in blind fumbling trying to find out which key has been mismapped to which other key despite the letter on the top.
<br />

<br />
Trust me, coping with a qwerty 103 keyboard when you are used to a 101 qwerty keyboard is childs play by comparison.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
